      "text": "Based on the analysis of the spectroscopic data, the molecule is identified as the protected dipeptide **Boc-Phg-Ala-OtBu** (tert-butyl (2-((tert-butoxycarbonyl)amino)-2-phenylacetyl)alaninate).\n\nThe molecular formula **C20H30N2O5** matches the proposed structure. The **1H NMR** spectrum confirms the presence of a phenyl group (5H, 7.15–7.37 ppm) and the absence of benzylic methylene protons, indicating a phenylglycine (Phg) residue rather than phenylalanine. The multiplet at 4.46 ppm coupled to a methyl group (buried in the 1.25–1.45 ppm region) identifies an alanine (Ala) residue. The large integration in the aliphatic region (21H) accounts for the methyl group of alanine (3H) and two *tert*-butyl groups (9H + 9H), consistent with Boc and *tert*-butyl ester protection. The doublet at 6.34 ppm (amide NH) coupling to the alanine $\\alpha$-proton establishes the sequence as Phg-Ala (with Ala at the C-terminus). The **13C NMR** supports this with signals for carbamate, amide, and ester carbonyls, as well as distinct quaternary carbons for the two *tert*-butyl groups.\n\nFINAL_RESULT:\n  UUID: d677455f-772d-4c80-a382-aa671497e57b\n  PREDICTED_SMILES: CC(C)(C)OC(=O)NC(C1=CC=CC=C1)C(=O)NC(C)C(=O)OC(C)(C)C\n  CONFIDENCE: 0.95\n  REASON_BRIEF: The formula C20H30N2O5, combined with NMR evidence of a phenyl group, an alanine moiety, and two tert-butyl groups (Boc and ester), supports a protected dipeptide. The specific coupling of the amide doublet to the alanine alpha-proton confirms the sequence as Boc-Phg-Ala-OtBu.",
